The new anti-globalization reaction
PRINCETON – A palpable sense of unease was felt at the last G-7 summit in Ise-Shima, Japan.
At the next meeting of the leaders of the world's major developed economies, no one can say which of them will be part of the populist insurgents.
President Donald Trump could represent the United States, or President Marine Le Pen could represent France.
They could sit with British Prime Minister Boris Johnson, Italian Prime Minister Beppe Grillo, or even with German Chancellor Frauke Petry.
Each of them could become the champion of nationalism and isolationism, in one form or another.
The reaction against globalization has lasted for two decades.
By the end of the 20th century, the global trend appeared to be one of convergence, and people seemed to be consuming the same products everywhere.
McDonald's has illustrated this kind of globalization: breaking the windows of stores in this chain has become a standard form of protest against globalization.
But lately, the nature of globalization has changed, as has the reaction against it.
Although the world is increasingly interconnected, there is a sense that we understand foreigners less.
In response to the evolution of consumer preferences (which are increasingly sophisticated), companies are shifting their production closer to the markets where the goods will be sold.
This weakens the growth of international trade.
A similar "on-shore" anchoring is not new.
In the 1970s and 1980s, Americans feared that the United States would be flooded with Japanese automobiles. They then began producing these automobiles domestically.
Currently, most "Japanese" cars sold in the United States are actually manufactured in the United States. But the reversal of globalization of goods is now easier than ever, thanks to advancements in robotic engineering and the development of processes like 3D printing.
Thus, current criticism of globalization tends to focus less on commercial issues.
But this evolution does not reflect only the slowdown in trade growth.
The consumers in rich countries are much more at ease with foreign products; in some cases, they even depend on them, ranging from constantly updated electronics to inexpensive "fast fashion," which has become predominant in advanced economies.
Instead of rejecting foreign products, current opponents of globalization reject foreigners.
The disputes over investor protection clauses in trade agreements like the Trans-Pacific Partnership or the Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership focus on issues of obscure tribunals protecting foreign corporations' interests and allegedly undermining national sovereignty.
The next comes the global refugee crisis: in Europe, in particular, the anxiety over this influx may be a harbinger of a broader rejection of immigration from failed and impoverished states.
Why are the populations of advanced countries so afraid of foreigners?
It's not as if they had never been exposed to other cultures.
Many citizens of these countries frequently travel to distant destinations, and hundreds of millions of people around the world head each year to advanced countries.
The problem lies in our way of traveling.
Today, we tend more to experience things quickly and superficially rather than immerse ourselves in a culture.
But as modern game theory teaches, a one-time interaction is very different from continuous contact.
If participants know that they have a unique and limited experience, they have no interest in building a deeper base of understanding or cooperation.
A continuous exchange is necessary to foster trust.
The result of the superficial approach to current travels is evident for any major tourist destination.
Restaurants are unlikely to offer good or simply honest service to people who they are sure will never return.
The restaurants serve food that is mediocre (or worse) without a smile, the taxi drivers cheat you, and the hotel owners lie about their amenities.
Furthermore, this little game can suffer interruptions.
In places where tourism has become a source of foreign revenue, it also becomes an attractive target for terrorists who base their ideology on anti-Western resentment.
Some attacks in places like Bali or the Red Sea tourist complexes are sufficient to trigger a deep economic destabilization.
Tourism companies respond to such risks by minimizing contact with the local population.
The emblem of modern tourism is a gigantic cruise ship, where passengers can spend only a few hours at each destination (to visit a beautiful Caribbean island or an ancient port of the Mediterranean), but always sleep in the same bed.
The new Royal Caribbean cruise ship, Harmony of the Seas, aims to recreate all climates of the world.
Indeed, this ship, which is over 30 meters long and longer than the Eiffel Tower, contains a tropical park and an ice rink (in addition to its 23 pools and 42 bars).
Tourist bus and train companies do the same thing to ensure the safety of their passengers by only letting them off at famous sites for a limited time, in fact just long enough to take some photos.
This style of travel imposes a constraint on the local infrastructure capacity.
One often lacks space to walk along the canals of Venice or on the path that leads to the Acropolis.
This approach strengthens the mutual misunderstanding.
The visitors remain within the limits of their pre-planned excursions, meeting only scammers who offer them trinkets or wildly overpriced taxi rides.
The indigenous people do not appreciate the groups of tourists who gather around their most beautiful sites.
No one feels particularly involved, and no relationships of trust are maintained.
It's easy to feel a nostalgia for a time when tourism meant longer stays and longer-term encounters with very different cultures.
It would obviously be impossible, for the current number of visitors, to stay for weeks or months at a time in old monasteries.
But it is possible to imagine certain configurations in which visitors and their hosts could interact in a more personal way.
For example, Airbnb can provide a much more appealing experience than a hotel or, worse still, a cruise ship.
Is there an equivalent policy to Airbnb?
Could world leaders participate in summits like the G-7 by living and working for an extended period in a foreign country?
Soon after the United States entered World War II, Winston Churchill made this famous gesture of packing his bags to move into the White House for 24 days, in order to strengthen the transatlantic alliance with Britain by deepening his relationship with Franklin Roosevelt.
This level of familiarity could well be the populists' greatest enemy among the current altermondialiste movements.
